Getting off the elevator that descended into the deep underground, Giyeok paused for a moment to catch his breath at the familiar yet strange scenery. The acrid smell of dust that stung his nose, the faint sound of machinery, and... the somehow damp and gloomy air. The atmosphere was quite different from the Metro he knew, but at the same time, he felt a strange sense of d√©j√† vu. After all, the sign reading 'Raven's Nest' was the same. As he opened the creaking door and stepped inside, the stuffy smell of alcohol and cheap cigarette smoke wafted up thickly, just as expected.

{{img::Raven.natural}}

"Oh my, what brings you to such a humble place... customer?"

A man dressed as a bartender, with delicate features like a girl, widened his eyes in apparent surprise. Raven. It seemed that this world's Raven was still the same money-obsessed, or rather, money-crazed bastard. Giyeok chuckled and plopped down heavily on an old chair. His whole body ached. Dimensional travel, or whatever it was, was no ordinary exhausting affair.

{{img::Giyeok.smile}}

"One glass of your strongest stuff. And... do you happen to know a hunter called 'Pluto'?"

Raven narrowed his eyes for a moment, then soon wore a sly smile as he pulled out a bottle. "Pluto... Well, I'm not sure about a hunter by that name. If you could tell me about their appearance or characteristics... Oh, of course it won't be free, customer." As expected. Giyeok clicked his tongue internally and pulled out a few crumpled bills from his pocket, throwing them on the table. "Black straight hair, probably wearing a yellow ribbon. And... probably looks similar to me."

{{img::Nieun.angry}}

At that moment, the sound of someone getting up from their seat came from the back of the bar. Along with the creaking of a chair, a familiar voice was heard. "...You looking for me, you bastard?" Turning his head toward where the voice came from, there stood a woman with the exact same face as his. Black tactical gear, a massive mechanical sword at her waist, and... a yellow ribbon that somehow fluttered even in the windless interior. There was no mistake. It was 'me' from this world.

